<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-04-17T05:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-04-17T05:00:00-05:00" n="570" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d570">
                    <note rend="inline" type="source">761.93/1765: Telegram</note>
                    <head>
                        <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                        </hi>
                    </head>
                    <opener>
                        <dateline rendition="#right">
                            <placeName>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-04-17T17:00:00+07:00">April 17,
                                1944—5 p.m.</date>
                            <lb/> [Received April 17—3:17 p.m.]</dateline>
                    </opener>
                    <p>669. In reply to Embassy’s inquiry, Consul at Tihwa, in telegram April 13,
                        locates Fuwen (also known as Keketohai) 300 li southwest Chenghwasze and 164
                        li west of Chingho. Embassy’s 631, April 11.</p>
                    <p>Consul preparing tracing of map showing disputed boundaries (Embassy’s 585,
                        April 3) original of which obtained from Foreign Affairs Delegate.</p>
                    <closer>
                        <signed>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Gauss</hi>
                        </signed>
                    </closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>